         <div type="translation">
            <head>Translation</head>
            <p>i: You who are full of <supplied reason="subaudible">knowledge of</supplied> laws,
               who have blended the Italian Muse with the sweet-voiced honey of the Attic,
               Oikoumenios, the famous governor, the friendly council of the Aphrodisians has set
               you up here; for what greater reward than that of being well remembered can the man
               find who is pure in mind and in hand? </p>
            <p>ii: ?M<supplied reason="abbreviation">ary</supplied> b<supplied reason="abbreviation"
                  >ore</supplied> Ch<supplied reason="abbreviation">rist</supplied>. God, help.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>For i. see discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="III.33">III.33</xref>.</p>
            <p>For ii., the inscription on the head, see discussion at <xref type="eAla-text"
                  n="VIII.20">VIII.20</xref>, and compare <xref type="inscription" n="145"
                  href="150102">15.102</xref></p>
            <p>For the statue and the monument as whole, see <bibl type="hbi" n="rrrs2002"
                     ><author>Smith</author> 'The Statue Monument of Oecumenius: A New Portrait of a
                  Late Antique Governor from Aphrodisias' (JRS, <date value="1999" notBefore="1999"
                     notAfter="1999" exact="both">2002</date>), 134-156</bibl></p>
         </div>
         <div type="history" n="locations">
            <head>Locations</head>
            <p>Found: <rs type="found"><rs type="monuList">North Agora</rs>: standing against the
                  north wall of the north stoa. .</rs>. Original location: <rs type="origLocation"
                  >Findspot.</rs>. Last recorded location: <rs type="lastLocation">Findspot
               (1994).</rs>. </p>
         </div>


         <div type="history" n="record">
            <head>History of Recording</head>
            <p>The base and the body of the statue were excavated by the NYU expedition in 1965
               (base: <rs type="invNo">65.198</rs>); see <bibl><author>K. T. Erim</author> in <title
                     level="j">Turk Ark. Derg.</title> 15.1 (1966), 61</bibl>. The head was
               excavated in 2000.</p>
         </div>
